[[File:Konstanty Michalski.png|thumb|130px|Konstanty Michalski]] ''' Konstanty Michalski''' (1879–1947) was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[theologian]] and [[philosopher]].<ref>"Michalski, Konstanty," ''Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN'' (PWN Universal Encyclopedia), vol. 3, p. 104.</ref>
==Life== Michalski was a member of an order of missionary priests. From 1918 he was a professor of philosophy at—from 1931 rector of— [[Kraków]]'s [[Jagiellonian University]]. From 1927 he was a member of the [[Polish Academy of Learning]].<ref>"Michalski, Konstanty," ''Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN'' (PWN Universal Encyclopedia), vol. 3, p. 104.</ref>
Michalski was a leading Polish student of [[medieval philosophy]]. The chief object of his studies was late, especially 14th-century, [[Scholasticism]] and [[Nominalism]] in Poland.<ref>"Michalski, Konstanty," ''Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN'' (PWN Universal Encyclopedia), vol. 3, p. 104.</ref>
==Works== *''Tomizm w Polsce na przełomie XV i XVI w.'' ([[Thomism]] in [[Poland]] at the Turn of the 15th and 16th Centuries; 1911) *''Odrodzenie nominalizmu w XIV w.'' (The Rebirth of Nominalism in the 14th Century; 1926).<ref>"Michalski, Konstanty," ''Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN'' (PWN Universal Encyclopedia), vol. 3, p. 104.</ref>
