'''Margaret Urban Walker''' (born August 8, 1948),<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Walker, Margaret Urban, 1948- |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n97062272.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 9 October 2015 |quote= data sheet (b. Aug. 8, 1948) }}</ref> is the Donald J. Schuenke Chair Emerita in Philosophy at [[Marquette University]].<ref name=apa>{{cite web|last=DesAutels|first=Peggy|title=March 2012: Margaret Urban Walker|url=http://www.apaonlinecsw.org/home/woman_philosopher/margareturbanwalker|work=Highlighted Philosophers|publisher=American Philosophical Association|accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=biog>{{cite web|title=Margaret Urban Walker|url=http://www.marquette.edu/phil/faculty_walker.shtml|publisher=Marquette University|accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref> Before her appointment at Marquette, she was the Lincoln Professor of Ethics at [[Arizona State University]], and before that she was at [[Fordham University]].<ref name=biog/>  She has also previously held visiting appointments at Washington University at St. Louis, the University of South Florida, and the Catholic University of Leuven.<ref name=biog/>

In 2002, Walker was awarded the Cardinal Mercier chair at the Catholic University of Leuven, and was the first woman ever to hold the chair.<ref name=biog/>

==Education and career==
Walker (born Margaret Urban)<ref name=VIAF>{{cite web |title= Walker, Margaret Urban, 1948-... |url= https://viaf.org/viaf/16510471/#Walker,_Margaret_Urban,_1948-.... |publisher= [[Virtual International Authority File|VIAF]] |accessdate= 9 October 2015  }}</ref> received her bachelor's in philosophy from the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] in 1969.<ref name=cv>{{cite web|last=Urban Walker|first=Margaret|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://www.marquette.edu/phil/documents/WalkerCV2012.pdf|publisher=Marquette|accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref> She went on to receive her master's in philosophy from [[Northwestern University]] in 1971, and her doctorate in philosophy, also from Northwestern, in 1975.<ref name=cv/>

Walker was a member of the Philosophy Department at [[Fordham University]] for 28 years before moving to [[Arizona State University]] from 2002 to 2010 (where she received the Defining Edge Research in the Humanities Award in 2007), and moving to [[Marquette University]] in 2010.<ref name=cv/> She retired in May 2017.<ref name=academia>{{cite web|title=Margaret Urban Walker|url=https://marquette.academia.edu/MargaretUrbanWalker|publisher=Academia.edu|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> She held visiting appointments at Washington University at St. Louis, the University of South Florida, and the Catholic University of Leuven.<ref name=cv/>  During her second visiting appointment at the Catholic University of Leuven, she was the first woman to hold the Cardinal Mercier Chair in Philosophy.<ref name=biog/>  She also was a Laurance S. Rockefeller Fellow at [[Princeton University]]'s Center for Human Values from 2003 to 2004.<ref name=biog/>

==Research areas==
Walker's recent research has focused on repairing [[moral relations]] after wrongdoing, especially in relation to political violence.<ref name=eoc>{{cite web|last=Urban Walker|first=Margaret|title=Margaret Urban Walker - Ethics of care|url=http://ethicsofcare.org/interviews/margaret-urban-walker/|publisher=Ethics of Care|accessdate=18 August 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315085556/http://ethicsofcare.org/interviews/margaret-urban-walker/|archivedate=15 March 2013|df=}}</ref><ref name=biog/> She has contributed to research projects with the International Center for Transitional Justice on gender and reparations and truth commissions.<ref name=cv/> She was drawn to this area through her earlier work, in which she focused on the effects of social inequalities on the way morality is understood in ethics and everyday life.<ref name=biog/> Some of her earlier research focused on developing a [[social difference]]s-focused approach to ethical theory.<ref name=eoc/> She strongly defends the view that although moral understandings are inextricably linked to the historical and social practices that they derived from, that those historical and social practices not only can be, but must be critically assessed.<ref name=apa/>

